text.section:
There is no privilege if:
A disclosure is necessary for the purpose of placing the client in a facility for mental illness;
A judge finds that the client, after being informed there will be no privilege, makes communications in the course of an examination ordered by the court;
In a civil or criminal proceeding:
The client introduces the client's mental condition as an element of the claim or defense; or
After the client's death, the client's mental condition is introduced by any party claiming or defending through or as a beneficiary of the client;
The client or the personal representative of the client makes a claim against the licensed certified social worker for malpractice; or
The client expressly consents to waive the privilege, or in the case of death or disability, the client's personal representative waives the privilege for purpose of making a claim or bringing suit on a policy of insurance on life, health, or physical condition.

There is no privilege in:
Any administrative or judicial nondelinquent juvenile proceeding;
Any guardianship and adoption proceeding initiated by a child placement agency;
Any guardianship and protective services proceeding concerning disabled persons; or
Any criminal or delinquency proceeding in which there is a charge of child abuse or neglect or which arises out of an investigation of suspected child abuse or neglect.
